author: Scotland‚Äôs Coefficient
text:
Of course Rangers could (and will want to) avoid #UCL qual. altogether by either recovering in the league (nabbing the almost certain auto #UCL group spot) or by winning #UEL 

But if they lose to Leipzig then they need to hope the Germans stay top 4 AND win #UEL

author: Scotland‚Äôs Coefficient
text:
Now the tricky part here is only Leipzig are currently on track to do that (4th in üá©üá™ by 3pts).

Frankfurt are 12pts off a #UCL spot with 5 games left.

West Ham are 6pts off a #UCL spot with 6 games left (but have played a game more)

author: Scotland‚Äôs Coefficient
text:
So being seeded is an advantage yes.  But the bigger thing Rangers fans should hope for is this:

If this season's #UEL winner ALSO qualifies for next season's #UCL group stage via their domestic league, then 2nd place in üè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å≥Û†Å£Û†Å¥Û†Åø (as well as 2nd place in üá¶üáπ) would move from Q2 to Q3

author: Scotland‚Äôs Coefficient
text:
But being seeded doesn't take away from the fact that the #UCL League Path is the most difficult qualification route.  And on paper at the moment Rangers would have to play three ties.

Remember, Rangers lost to Malmo as a seed this year.

text:
